Yes - that is the right product direction. **Mimo should speak, understand, and physically react**, while your desktop and mobile apps become the "control + brain + integrations" layer.

## Core idea

Mimo should work like this:

```text
User speaks
   ↓
Mobile/Desktop app captures audio
   ↓
Mimo Brain backend understands intent
   ↓
AI chooses response + emotion + physical action
   ↓
Mimo speaks + moves + changes face/LEDs
   ↓
Action executes: desktop, TV, AC, smart home, reminders, etc.
```

Your ESP32-S3 robot should **not** directly run heavy voice AI. It should receive simple commands:

```json
{
  "mood": "happy",
  "face": "smile_big",
  "animation": "wave_left",
  "sound": "happy_001",
  "led": "blue_pulse"
}
```

The mobile/desktop/backend system handles the real intelligence.

## Best scalable voice architecture

You can build two modes.

### Mode 1 - Fast and reliable: app-based voice

This is what I recommend first.

```text
Phone/Desktop mic
-> speech-to-text
-> AI brain
-> text-to-speech
-> phone/desktop speaker or Mimo speaker
-> ESP32 action command
```

This is easier because your phone/laptop already has a good microphone and speaker. OpenAI's Audio API supports speech-to-text, and its speech docs describe both speech-to-text and text-to-speech tasks, including streaming spoken output. ([developers.openai.com][1])

### Mode 2 - More advanced: realtime voice conversation

Later, use realtime speech-to-speech:

```text
Phone/Desktop app
-> Realtime AI session
-> live voice response
-> tool calls
-> Mimo movement/actions
```

OpenAI's Realtime API supports WebRTC connections for realtime models, and the Realtime conversations docs cover audio/text generation, image input, and function calling event flows. ([developers.openai.com][2])

## Reaction engine

This is the part that makes Mimo feel alive.

Every AI response should produce **three outputs**:

```json
{
  "speech": "Of course! I turned on focus mode for you.",
  "emotion": "helpful_happy",
  "actions": [
    { "type": "face", "name": "smile" },
    { "type": "servo", "name": "nod" },
    { "type": "led", "name": "blue_pulse" },
    { "type": "desktop", "name": "start_focus_timer", "minutes": 45 }
  ]
}
```

So Mimo does not just answer. It **answers + feels + moves + acts**.

## Software modules to build

Your scalable app should have these modules:

```text
mimo-brain/
  voice/
    stt.py                  # speech to text
    tts.py                  # text to speech
    realtime_session.py     # later
  agents/
    personality_agent.py
    command_router.py
    emotion_engine.py
    safety_guard.py
    memory_agent.py
  skills/
    robot_actions.py
    desktop_actions.py
    smart_home_actions.py
    tv_actions.py
    ac_actions.py
    reminders.py
    coding_assistant.py
  integrations/
    home_assistant.py
    mqtt_client.py
    esp32_client.py
  storage/
    memory.db
    conversations.db
```

Desktop app:

```text
mimo-desktop/
  tray app
  microphone capture
  push-to-talk / wake mode
  desktop skills
  safe command approval
  local file/project helper
```

Mobile app:

```text
mimo-mobile/
  voice remote
  robot control
  mood/personality settings
  smart home shortcuts
  logs
  routines
```

ESP32 firmware:

```text
mimo-firmware/
  display_face
  servo_controller
  led_controller
  sensor_reader
  sound_player
  command_receiver
  telemetry_sender
```

## How Mimo understands commands

Do not hardcode everything as simple text matching. Use **tool/function calling**.

Example tool list:

```json
[
  {
    "name": "set_mimo_emotion",
    "description": "Change Mimo's face, LED color, and body mood.",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "emotion": {
          "type": "string",
          "enum": ["happy", "sad", "sleepy", "curious", "excited", "focused"]
        }
      },
      "required": ["emotion"]
    }
  },
  {
    "name": "control_smart_home",
    "description": "Control a smart home device through Home Assistant.",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "device": { "type": "string" },
        "action": { "type": "string" }
      },
      "required": ["device", "action"]
    }
  }
]
```

OpenAI's function-calling docs describe this exact pattern: models can connect to external systems and actions provided by your application through structured tools. ([developers.openai.com][3])

## Smart home, TV, AC

For this, use **Home Assistant as the bridge**.

Mimo should not directly support every TV/AC brand from day one. Instead:

```text
Mimo -> Home Assistant -> TV / AC / lights / plugs / sensors
```

Home Assistant provides a REST API on the same port as the frontend, with JSON requests/responses, and also has WebSocket APIs used by its frontend/backend communication. ([developers.home-assistant.io][4])

Example Mimo commands:

```text
"Mimo, turn on the TV"
"Mimo, set AC to 23 degrees"
"Mimo, make the room cozy"
"Mimo, start movie mode"
"Mimo, turn off all lights"
```

Behind the scenes:

```json
{
  "skill": "home_assistant",
  "domain": "climate",
  "entity_id": "climate.living_room_ac",
  "service": "set_temperature",
  "data": { "temperature": 23 }
}
```

## Personality system

Mimo should have a persistent personality file:

```yaml
name: Mimo
core_traits:
  - curious
  - playful
  - helpful
  - slightly shy when idle
  - excited when praised

moods:
  happy:
    face: smile_big
    led: blue_pulse
    servo: happy_wiggle
    voice_style: warm
  sleepy:
    face: sleepy_eyes
    led: dim_blue
    servo: slow_nod
    voice_style: soft
  focused:
    face: calm
    led: steady_blue
    servo: still
    voice_style: precise
```

Then every reply becomes:

```text
intent + personality + mood + action
```

This is what makes it feel like a pet, not just a speaker.

## Memory

Add memory in layers:

```text
Short-term memory:
- current conversation
- current mood
- last command

Daily memory:
- what you worked on today
- reminders
- tasks
- routines

Long-term memory:
- your preferences
- favorite devices
- project folders
- common commands
- personality evolution
```

Example:

```text
"Mimo, start my coding mode."
```

Mimo remembers:

```text
open VS Code
turn AC to 23
turn on desk light
start 50-minute focus timer
set Mimo mood to focused
```

## Safety rules

This is very important because you want desktop + smart home control.

Use this policy:

```text
Low-risk actions: run immediately
- change face
- move servo
- play sound
- turn LED on
- show weather
- start timer

Medium-risk actions: ask confirmation
- turn off TV
- change AC temperature
- send message
- open project files

High-risk actions: blocked by default
- delete files
- run shell commands
- install apps
- expose secrets
- make payments
- unlock doors
```

Also keep API keys only on your backend/server. OpenAI's API docs say API keys should not be exposed in client-side code such as browsers or apps, and should be loaded from environment variables or a server-side key-management service. ([developers.openai.com][5])

## Best development order

### Phase 1 - Mimo reacts without AI

```text
Mobile/Desktop button -> backend -> ESP32
```

Commands:

```text
smile
sad
blink
wave
nod
play sound
set LED color
```

### Phase 2 - Mimo understands text

```text
You type: "Mimo, be happy"
AI returns:
- speech
- emotion
- robot actions
```

### Phase 3 - Mimo understands voice

```text
Push-to-talk in mobile/desktop app
-> STT
-> AI
-> TTS
-> robot reaction
```

### Phase 4 - Smart home skills

```text
Home Assistant integration
TV mode
AC mode
lights mode
routines
```

### Phase 5 - Realtime conversation

```text
Low-latency voice
interruptions
natural conversation
function calling
live robot reactions
```

## Final architecture recommendation

Build Mimo as:

```text
React Native mobile app
+ Tauri or Electron desktop app
+ FastAPI brain backend
+ MQTT/WebSocket robot protocol
+ ESP32-S3 body firmware
+ Home Assistant integration
+ OpenAI voice/text layer
```

That is fully scalable. You can add more skills forever without changing the robot body too much.

The most important design rule:

```text
Every feature becomes a plugin/skill.
Every Mimo reaction becomes emotion + face + servo + LED + sound.
Every dangerous action needs confirmation.
```

That will let Mimo speak, understand, react, control your devices, help with desktop work, and grow into a real product platform.

